benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/export/{accountId} - Export account data

covered: Valid Request: Scenarios cover successful export (TC01, TC02, TC06, TC14).
Authorization: Tests include 401 when authentication is missing (TC18).

Error Handling: Numerous negative test cases cover 400 for bad input (TC04, TC11), 400 for missing required header (TC03), 404 for non-existent account (TC05), 404 for missing path (TC12), 500 when export service is unavailable (TC10), 504 timeout (TC17).
HTTP Method Compliance: 405 for unsupported HTTP method (TC16).
Concurrency/Performance: Concurrent requests (TC13) and slow downstream (TC09) and large data (TC08) scenarios address performance and concurrency aspects.
Backward/Regression coverage: Regression test for Content-Type (TC14) and legacy header support (TC15).
Accessibility: Accessibility test (TC19) addresses discoverability of API docs.
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination handling for large datasets across exported data.
Caching Behavior: No tests verify caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or related caching behavior.
Rate Limiting: No tests validate behavior under rapid/ burst of requests or throttling.
Empty data scenario: No explicit test for exporting when account has data but archive is effectively empty (edge case).
Query Parameters: No explicit tests exploring variations in optional query parameters (if any beyond path/header).
recommendations: Add a dedicated pagination test to verify handling when exporting accounts with very large datasets (verify correct paging or streaming behavior if applicable).
Add tests for caching behavior (ETag, Cache-Control) to ensure proper client-side caching and revalidation semantics.
Add rate-limiting/throttling tests to ensure proper handling of bursts (e.g., multiple rapid requests).
Add an explicit test for the empty-export scenario (account with data that results in an empty archive, if business logic allows), and verify correct status and messaging.
Consider explicit tests for invalid/expired tokens and 403 vs 401 distinctions if authorization scope is relevant.
